---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

// Utility manifest quickstart — hand-authored walkthrough.
// Writes the smallest useful manifest end to end. A single public HTTP fetch,
// one emit, one row. Once this works, the rest of the spec is incremental.
//
// Voice: short, plain punctuation, no em-dashes, no section symbol.
// Examples use generic placeholder names (Acme) so this is safe to publish.
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Quickstart: write your first Bolt App | Sparcle"
  description="Build your first custom Bolt App in under 5 minutes. A single YAML manifest, one HTTP call, one typed row. End-to-end walkthrough with a runnable example."
  canonical="https://sparcle.app/docs/utilities/quickstart"
>
  <main class="qs-page">
    <section class="qs-hero">
      <div class="container">
        <p class="qs-eyebrow"><a href="/docs/utilities">&larr; Apps</a></p>
        <h1>Quickstart.</h1>
        <p class="qs-lede">
          Write your first Bolt App in under 5 minutes. We'll build
          a tiny <code>=worldclock</code> chip that hits a public HTTP endpoint
          and emits one <code>Event</code> row showing the current time in a
          given zone. Once this works, every richer manifest (MCP calls, multiple
          scopes, filters, actions) is incremental.
        </p>
        <ul class="qs-pills">
          <li><a href="/docs/utilities/spec">Full spec (v1) &rarr;</a></li>
          <li><a href="/docs/utilities/gallery">Sample gallery &rarr;</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="qs-section">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>What you'll write</h2>
        <p>
          A single YAML file. Bolt loads it at startup (or hot-reloads it from
          the admin UI). When the user types <code>=worldclock tokyo</code> in
          the launcher, Bolt parses the manifest, runs the declared HTTP call,
          and shows the result row in the autocomplete dropdown.
        </p>
        <p>
          Every manifest has the same shape. You're declaring four things:
        </p>
        <ol class="qs-bullets numbered">
          <li><strong>Identity.</strong> How the chip is named, versioned, and what type of row it emits.</li>
          <li><strong>Scopes.</strong> Sub-commands the user can pick. The minimum is one.</li>
          <li><strong>Flow.</strong> A list of declarative steps (<code>call</code>, <code>parallel</code>, <code>merge</code>, <code>transform</code>, <code>emit</code>).</li>
          <li><strong>Emit.</strong> How response fields map into the canonical row type.</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="qs-section">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>The whole file</h2>
        <p class="qs-section-blurb">
          Save this as <code>worldclock.yaml</code> under your Bolt sync
          directory (or paste it into the YAML side panel in the admin UI). The
          full reference for every field is in the <a href="/docs/utilities/spec">manifest spec</a>.
        </p>
        <pre class="qs-block"><code>{`schema_version: 1
id: worldclock
chip: =worldclock
title: World Clock
description: Current time for a given timezone.
emits: Event

scopes:
  - id: lookup
    match: "{zone:string}"
    flow:
      - call:
          id: fetch_time
          kind: http
          public: true
          method: GET
          url: "https://worldtimeapi.org/api/timezone/\${zone}"
      - emit:
          from: fetch_time
          fields:
            title: "Current time in \${zone}"
            subtitle: "\${.datetime}"
            timezone: "\${.timezone}"
            utc_offset: "\${.utc_offset}"

presentation:
  empty_state: "Try =worldclock America/New_York"
`}</code></pre>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="qs-section">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>What each block does</h2>

        <h3>Identity</h3>
        <p>
          <code>schema_version: 1</code> pins this manifest to the v1 parser.
          <code>id</code> is the unique key used in audit logs and admin UI.
          <code>chip: =worldclock</code> is what the user types in the launcher.
          <code>emits: Event</code> tells Bolt which canonical row type the
          emitted rows conform to. Bolt knows how to render <code>Event</code> in
          the launcher and the right rail without any extra config.
        </p>

        <h3>Scopes</h3>
        <p>
          Every manifest needs at least one scope. <code>match</code> is the
          pattern that follows the chip. <code>{`"{zone:string}"`}</code> means
          the user types one free-form string after <code>=worldclock</code>,
          and it's captured as the template variable <code>${`\${zone}`}</code>.
          See the <a href="/docs/utilities/spec#5-scopes">Scopes section</a> for
          the full set of match patterns.
        </p>

        <h3>Flow</h3>
        <p>
          A flow is a list of steps. <code>call</code> runs one tool. This call
          is <code>kind: http</code> with <code>public: true</code>, which lets
          Bolt skip the per-user OAuth handshake (the endpoint requires no
          credentials). Most real utilities hit private MCP tools or
          authenticated HTTP endpoints; see
          <a href="/docs/utilities/spec#6-flow-dag">Flow DAG</a> for
          <code>parallel</code>, <code>merge</code>, and <code>transform</code>.
        </p>

        <h3>Emit</h3>
        <p>
          The <code>emit</code> step takes the response of a prior call and
          binds its fields into a row of the declared canonical type.
          <code>${`\${.field}`}</code> reads from the most recent call's response
          body. <code>${`\${zone}`}</code> reads from the scope match. The full
          binding grammar is in
          <a href="/docs/utilities/spec#6-5-emit-produce-the-final-row-set">Emit</a>.
        </p>

        <h3>Presentation</h3>
        <p>
          Optional. <code>empty_state</code> is what the launcher shows when
          the chip has no input yet. The
          <a href="/docs/utilities/spec#11-presentation">Presentation</a> section
          covers the full list (icons, right-rail widget binding, empty-state
          variants).
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="qs-section">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>Try it</h2>
        <ol class="qs-bullets numbered">
          <li>Open the admin UI, go to <strong>Utilities &rarr; Custom</strong>, click <strong>New manifest</strong>.</li>
          <li>Paste the YAML above. Save.</li>
          <li>Open the launcher. Type <code>=worldclock America/New_York</code>.</li>
          <li>You should see one row with the current time. The right rail shows the full timezone block.</li>
        </ol>
        <p class="qs-section-blurb">
          If the manifest fails to parse, the admin UI shows the line and column
          of the first error. Validation rules are listed in the
          <a href="/docs/utilities/spec#4-2-validation">spec section on validation</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="qs-section">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>Where to go next</h2>
        <ul class="qs-bullets">
          <li><a href="/docs/utilities/gallery">Sample gallery.</a> Real-world manifests for Jira, Salesforce, Slack, Notion, Linear, GitHub, and more. Fork one as a starting point for your own.</li>
          <li><a href="/docs/utilities/spec">Full manifest spec (v1).</a> Every field, every step kind, every validation rule. The source of truth.</li>
          <li><a href="/docs/utilities/spec#5-scopes">Scopes.</a> Add a second scope (e.g. <code>=acme my</code> vs <code>=acme search</code>).</li>
          <li><a href="/docs/utilities/spec#6-flow-dag">Flow DAG.</a> Fan out with <code>parallel</code>, merge with <code>merge</code>, reshape with <code>transform</code>.</li>
          <li><a href="/docs/utilities/spec#8-actions">Actions.</a> Add typed actions on rows (open in source, run a tool, pipe into the composer).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="qs-section qs-section-final">
      <div class="container">
        <p class="qs-footnote">
          Stuck on something this page should have covered? Reach the team via
          the contact link in the footer. Manifest authoring questions get
          priority routing.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <style>
    .qs-page {
      background: var(--bg-body);
      min-height: 100vh;
    }
    .qs-page .container {
      max-width: 1180px;
      margin: 0 auto;
      padding: 0 1.5rem;
    }

    .qs-hero {
      padding: calc(var(--nav-height, 80px) + 2.5rem) 0 1.5rem;
    }
    .qs-eyebrow {
      margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
      font-size: 0.85rem;
      color: var(--text-muted);
    }
    .qs-eyebrow a {
      color: var(--text-muted);
      text-decoration: none;
    }
    .qs-eyebrow a:hover { color: var(--brand-accent); }
    .qs-hero h1 {
      font-size: clamp(2.25rem, 4.5vw, 3.25rem);
      letter-spacing: -0.02em;
      color: var(--text-heading);
      margin: 0 0 1rem 0;
      line-height: 1.05;
    }
    .qs-lede {
      font-size: 1.05rem;
      line-height: 1.55;
      color: var(--text-body);
      margin: 0 0 1.5rem;
      max-width: 65ch;
    }
    .qs-pills {
      list-style: none;
      padding: 0;
      margin: 0;
      display: flex;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
      gap: 0.6rem;
    }
    .qs-pills a {
      display: inline-block;
      padding: 0.55rem 1rem;
      background: var(--bg-elevated);
      border: 1px solid var(--border-default);
      border-radius: 0.5rem;
      color: var(--text-heading);
      text-decoration: none;
      font-size: 0.875rem;
      font-weight: 500;
      transition: border-color 0.15s, background 0.15s;
    }
    .qs-pills a:hover {
      border-color: var(--brand-primary);
      background: var(--brand-primary-light);
    }

    .qs-section {
      padding: 2rem 0;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--border-default);
    }
    .qs-section-final {
      padding-bottom: 5rem;
    }
    .qs-section h2 {
      margin: 0 0 1rem;
      font-size: 1.5rem;
      color: var(--text-heading);
      letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    }
    .qs-section h3 {
      margin: 1.25rem 0 0.4rem;
      font-size: 1.05rem;
      color: var(--text-heading);
      font-weight: 700;
    }
    .qs-section p {
      margin: 0 0 1rem;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      line-height: 1.65;
      color: var(--text-body);
      max-width: 72ch;
    }
    .qs-section-blurb {
      margin: 0 0 1rem;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      line-height: 1.6;
      color: var(--text-body);
    }
    .qs-footnote {
      font-size: 0.85rem;
      color: var(--text-muted);
      margin: 0;
    }

    .qs-bullets {
      margin: 0 0 1rem;
      padding-left: 1.25rem;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      line-height: 1.65;
      color: var(--text-body);
      max-width: 72ch;
    }
    .qs-bullets li {
      margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
    }
    .qs-bullets.numbered {
      list-style: decimal;
    }
    .qs-bullets a,
    .qs-section p a {
      color: var(--brand-accent);
      text-decoration: none;
    }
    .qs-bullets a:hover,
    .qs-section p a:hover {
      text-decoration: underline;
    }

    .qs-block {
      margin: 0.5rem 0 1.25rem;
      background: var(--bg-elevated);
      border: 1px solid var(--border-default);
      border-radius: 0.5rem;
      padding: 0.85rem 1rem;
      overflow-x: auto;
      font-size: 0.85rem;
      line-height: 1.55;
    }
    .qs-block code,
    p code,
    li code {
      font-family: "SF Mono", Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
      color: var(--text-body);
    }
    .qs-block code {
      background: transparent;
      padding: 0;
      font-size: inherit;
    }
    p code,
    li code {
      background: var(--bg-muted);
      border: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
      padding: 0.08em 0.35em;
      border-radius: 4px;
      font-size: 0.88em;
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
